Philippine Stocks: ATR Kim Eng, Lepanto, Lopez, San Miguel

-- B y   B e r n i   M o e s t a f a
-- 
2011-06-30T04:53:46Z

-- http://www.bloomberg.com/news/2011-06-30/philippine-stocks-ayala-lepanto-consolidated-lopez-holdings.html
Shares of the following companies
had unusual moves in Philippine trading. Stock symbols are in
parentheses and prices are as of the noon close in Manila.  The Philippine Stock Exchange Index advanced 41.86 points,
or 1 percent, to 4,291.21. The gauge has increased 5.8 percent
this quarter.  ATR Kim Eng Financial Corp. (ATRK)  , which offers
financial services in the Philippines, jumped 7.8 percent to
4.15 pesos, the highest close since Feb. 7. Kim Eng Holdings
Ltd. will acquire ATR Holdings Inc.’s shares in the company to
eventually own 74.6 percent, it said in a statement to the stock
exchange. Kim Eng will buy ATR Holdings’s 32.2 percent stake at
4.15 pesos each, or for a total of 1.43 billion pesos ($43
million), the statement said.  Lepanto Consolidated Mining (LC)  Co, a metals producer,
rose 2.2 percent to 92 centavos, the steepest gain since June
15.  Philex Mining Corp. (PX)   is “open” to increasing its
stake in Lepanto, the Philippine Star reported today, citing
Philex Chairman Manuel Pangilinan. Philex advanced 3.3 percent
to 23.25 pesos. Pangilinan couldn’t be reached when called at
his office during lunch hour.  Lopez Holdings Corp. (LPZ)  , which has investments in
media and energy, climbed 2.5 percent to 5.74 pesos, the most
since May 31. The company is aiming to restructure all its
outstanding debt by the end of the year, the Philippine Daily
Inquirer reported. Angel S. Ong, president at Lopez, couldn’t be
reached when called at the company’s office in Pasig City.  San Miguel Corp. (SMC)  , the nation’s largest food and
drinks company, rose 1.1 percent to 115.20 pesos, the highest
close since June 8. The company will bid for power plants to be
auctioned by the government and may sell some former state
assets it already owns, President Ramon Ang said.  San Miguel  had
a “good” profit in the second quarter, Ang said in an
interview yesterday.  Trans-Asia Oil & Energy Development (TA)  Corp, an oil
explorer and energy company, surged 11 percent, the most since
Sept. 4, 2009, to 1.17 pesos.  Ayala Corp. (AC)  , owner of the
largest Philippine property developer, said one of its units
signed an agreement with Trans-Asia to build and operate a 135-
megawatt power plant in Batangas province. Ayala climbed 1.2
percent to 319 pesos.  To contact the reporter on this story:
